                <head>300. Summary of Conclusions of a Policy Review Committee Meeting<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d300fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_CJEJ_1"
                            >Carter</persName> Library, National Security Council, Institutional
                        Files, Box 68, <gloss target="#t_PRC_1">PRC</gloss> 053, 2/22/78,
                        International Economics. Confidential. The meeting took place in the White
                        House Situation Room. <persName corresp="#p_EGF_1">Erb</persName> sent the
                        Summary of Conclusions to <persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName>
                        under cover of a February 27 memorandum in which he noted that it “reflects
                        the discussions after the <gloss target="#t_PRC_1">PRC</gloss> meeting
                        between <persName corresp="#p_CRN_1">Dick Cooper</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_SAM_1">Tony Solomon</persName> that resulted in a decision
                        to support, if asked, the section of the <persName corresp="#p_HHH_1"
                            >Humphrey</persName> Bill on retroactive terms adjustment of the debt of
                        the least developed developing countries.” <persName corresp="#p_EGF_1"
                            >Erb</persName> reported that “[o]ther agencies have agreed to approve
                        the decision to support the debt section of the <persName corresp="#p_HHH_1"
                            >Humphrey</persName> Bill and State, Treasury, and <gloss
                            target="#t_AID_1">AID</gloss> have approved the summary as it now
                        stands.” (Ibid.) In a February 27 memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_ADL_1"
                            >Aaron</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_EGF_1">Erb</persName> commented
                        that “Treasury resisted change hedgerow-by-hedgerow. State, <gloss
                            target="#t_AID_1">AID</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>
                        were in favor. <gloss target="#t_OMB_1">OMB</gloss> acquiesced, but with
                        little enthusiasm. Agriculture supported the decision. Defense was
                        indifferent.” (<persName corresp="#p_CJEJ_1">Carter</persName> Library,
                        National Security Council, Institutional Files, Box 25, <gloss
                            target="#t_PRM_1">PRM</gloss> 08 [1 of 3] [1])</note>
                </head>
